  "What is the future value (FV) formula used to determine?": "",
  "How much a past investment lost, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "How much a current sum of money will grow to at a given interest rate over a specified period": "",
  "The amount of tax owed on gains, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "The current price of a stock, as conventional future theory would suggest": "",
  "The future value formula FV = PV × (1 + r)^n calculates how much a present sum will be worth at a future date given a specific interest rate and time period.": "",
  "What does NPV (Net Present Value) measure?": "",
  "The annual profit of a business": "",
  "The difference between the present value of cash inflows and the initial investment cost": "",
  "The maximum amount a company can borrow": "",
  "The total revenue of a project": "",
  "NPV discounts all future cash flows back to today's dollars and subtracts the initial cost. A positive NPV means the project creates value above the required return.": "",
  "What is the internal rate of return (IRR)?": "",
  "The discount rate that makes the NPV of a project equal to zero": "",
  "The interest rate a bank charges on loans": "",
  "The inflation rate for the year": "",
  "The maximum return on a savings account": "",
  "IRR is the discount rate at which NPV = 0. If the IRR exceeds the required rate of return (hurdle rate), the project should be accepted.": "",
  "What does EAR (Effective Annual Rate) represent?": "",
  "The rate before inflation adjustment": "",
  "The nominal rate stated by the bank": "",
  "The true annual return after accounting for compounding frequency": "",
  "The Federal Reserve's target rate": "",
  "EAR = (1 + r/n)^n - 1 converts a nominal rate with compounding into the actual annual yield. For example, 12% compounded monthly has an EAR of 12.68%.": "",
  "What is the Sharpe ratio used to measure?": "",
  "The price-to-earnings ratio of a stock": "",
  "Total return of an investment": "",
  "The total value of a portfolio": "",
  "Risk-adjusted return: how much excess return an investment earns per unit of risk": "",
  "Sharpe ratio = (Return - Risk-Free Rate) / Standard Deviation. A higher Sharpe ratio indicates better return per unit of risk, making it useful for comparing investments.": "",
